@jihoonson BTW, I have a couple of my own design concerns and I welcome your thoughts on the matter:
1. The complexity of `MovingAverageIterable`. But I would be careful in changing that for the sake of refactoring.
2. `Averager` implements their own accumulation formulas (computeResults) which are separate from the formulas of `Aggregator`. I think this could be refactored in order to easily add more types of Averagers and perhaps in order to allign null-handling with the new standards.

@gianm This is still an issue any chance this might work its way into a release? This impacts me greatly and I have to go to more work/less efficient queries to work around it. Basically any query using an origin of greater than the 28th of the month binning on monthly period breaks if it's over months that don't contain that day. 

For example a query with a granularity spec of 
```
"granularity": { "type": "period", "period": "P1M", "timeZone": "+00:00", "origin": "2017-07-31T00:00:00Z" }
```
and intervals of ["2017-07-31T00:00:00.000Z/2018-07-31T00:00:00.000Z"] throws the above error because there are months that don't have the 31st in them.

@gianm 
Though we have tried with `Transform Specs` using `cast` function Still we couldn't able to achieve  it.
```js
"transformSpec": {
        "transforms": [
          {
            "type": "expression",
            "name": "edata_visits_index",
            "expression": "cast(edata_visits_index,'LONG')"
          }
        ]
}
```
**Output:**  

```js
[
  {
    "segmentId": "datasource-events-33_2019-11-07T00:00:00.000Z_2019-11-08T00:00:00.000Z_2019-02-26T07:42:38.349Z",
    "columns": [
      "edata_visits_index"
    ],
    "events": [
      {
        "__time": 1573146630927,
        "edata_visits_index": "0"
      }
    ]
  }
]
```

Any other alternative solution to convert the `String` value into `Long` type

